<paragraph start="9" end="11">
<Alignment>1</Alignment>
<content start="9" end="10">
<component><class>org.concord.modeler.PageTextBox</class>
<width>750.0</width>
<height>320.0</height>
<title>&lt;html&gt;
  &lt;head&gt;
    
  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body marginheight=&quot;0&quot; face=&quot;verdana&quot; marginwidth=&quot;0&quot;&gt;
    &lt;table&gt;
      &lt;tr valign=&quot;top&quot;&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;
          &lt;img height=&quot;200&quot; src=&quot;balloon.png&quot; width=&quot;231&quot;&gt;
          
        &lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;
          Because electrons carry negative charges, they are affected when an 
          electric field is applied. For example, the electron cloud can 
          change shape. This change results in a process called &lt;b&gt;polarization&lt;/b&gt;, 
          which is what causes a charged balloon to stick on a wall (see the 
          illustration on the left).&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;In a very strong electric field, 
          the electrons of an atom or a molecule can escape from the 
          attraction of the nuclei and become free. This process is known as &lt;b&gt;ionization&lt;/b&gt;, 
          which is the mechanism that starts lightning.
        &lt;/td&gt;
        &lt;td&gt;
          &lt;img height=&quot;200&quot; src=&quot;lightning.gif&quot; width=&quot;150&quot;&gt;
          
        &lt;/td&gt;
      &lt;/tr&gt;
    &lt;/table&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
      On this page, you will explore these effects by applying an electric 
      field to an electron cloud.
    &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</title>
<opaque>false</opaque>
</component></content>

