  &lt;/head&gt;
  &lt;body marginheight=&quot;0&quot; face=&quot;verdana&quot; marginwidth=&quot;0&quot;&gt;
    To the right is a model of an atom with an electron cloud around the 
    nucleus. Initially, there is no electric field.

    &lt;p&gt;
      &lt;b&gt;Instructions:&lt;/b&gt;
    &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
      1. Click the &amp;quot;Run&amp;quot; button to start the simulation.&lt;br&gt;2. Use 
      the &amp;quot;Field intensity&amp;quot; slider to add an electric field and gradually 
      increase the intensity of the field. Observe what happens.&lt;br&gt;3. You may 
      use the &amp;quot;Field angle&amp;quot; slider to change the direction of the applied 
      electric field.&lt;br&gt;4. If the electron cloud disappears, click the &amp;quot;Reset 
      cloud&amp;quot; button to start over.
    &lt;/p&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;
      &lt;b&gt;Be sure to let the model run for a few seconds between each move&lt;/b&gt;.
    &lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;
</title>
<opaque>false</opaque>
</component></content>

